Justification:
Justification:
The Power Conditioning and Continuation Interfacing Equipment (PCCIE) program addresses critical Air Force infrastructure needs by ensuring the quality and continuity of electrical power supplied to essential
systems. The program mitigates risks associated with aging and obsolete Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) units that support mission-critical facilities, such as data centers, command and control systems,
radar, and medical infrastructure.
The PCCIE program prioritizes the replacement of aging UPS systems, focusing on units that have exceeded their operational lifespan of 12-15 years. The program ensures uninterrupted operations, reducing
downtime caused by electrical disturbances and outages.
Cost Justification:
1. Aging Equipment: Over 70% of UPS units in the Air Force inventory exceed 15 years of service, leading to increased failures and reduced reliability. The funding will enable the replacement of systems nearing
or beyond their lifespan.
2. Operational Continuity: Failure of UPS systems can lead to mission-critical downtime. This procurement ensures operational readiness by providing uninterrupted power to essential facilities.
3. Cost Savings: Modern UPS systems offer improved energy efficiency and reduced maintenance costs, providing a 30-50% reduction in lifecycle sustainment expenses.
4. Scalability and Flexibility: Procurement addresses immediate replacement needs while supporting future expansion and upgrades aligned with mission growth.




