 Justification:
 1. Mission Planning Systems (MPS) HARDWARE: Equips U.S. Air Force (USAF) operational flying units with hardware, software, warranties, and other services required to perform mission planning and
 integrate information with aircraft data transfer device systems. Aircraft supported include:

 Air Combat Command (ACC): F-15, F-16, F-22, F-35, A-10, E-3, E-4, E-7, RC/OC-135, HH-60, HC-130, EC-130, U-2, RQ-4

 Air Mobility Command (AMC): C-5, C-17, C-130, KC-10, KC-135, KC-46

 Air Force Global Strike Command (AFGSC): B-1, B-2, B-21, B-52, UH-1

 Air Education and Training Command (AETC): T-38, T-7A, T-1, T-6

 Procurement includes, but is not limited to, commercial-based Personal Computers (PCs) such as desktop computers, laptops, tablets, printers, storage devices, servers, displays, peripherals, software, software
 licenses, and support services. The program leverages advances in technology to enable high-end computing on smaller, more mission-oriented devices that provide sufficient processing power and memory to
 meet the demands of modern mission planning.

 All equipment will be centrally managed and distributed by the Mission Planning Systems Support Facility (MPSSF) and the Defense Logistics Agency.

 2. Joint Precision Airdrop System (JPADS) enables precision airdrop for logistical resupply and the delivery of diverse payloads. These payloads include kinetic effects, such as guided missiles capable of
 navigating to designated coordinates, and non-kinetic effects like sensors, communication nodes, and jammers, which rely on gravity for deployment.

 Key hardware components for procurement include Antenna Control Units (ACUs), Ultra High Frequency Receivers (UHFs), Modular Air Guidance Units (MAGUs), and dropsondes. JPADS delivers cargo
 accurately using ACUs and UHFs for guidance and communication, while MAGUs steer cargo precisely with onboard intelligence. Dropsondes provide real-time weather data, enabling optimal precision.
 Replacement of outdated Block 3.0 (UHFs and ACUs) systems with Block 4.1 systems (each consisting of one ACU and one UHF) is required to maintain compliance with Department of Defense (DoD)
 standards and address parts obsolescence. Essential for precision airdrop operations, these components are designed for roll-on/roll-off functionality where they can be easily loaded and unloaded from aircraft
 as needed for precision airdrop operations.

 AMC requires 170 new systems (163 replacements and 7 spares), totaling 340 subsystems (1 ACU and 1 UHF per system), by FY2028 to replace aging equipment and ensure mission readiness for precision
 airdrop. The upgrade is required to keep mobility aircraft equipped with reliable, repairable, and compliant equipment for precision airdrop capabilities. Costs for ACUs and UHFs average $40 thousand and $120
 thousand per unit respectively. Cost increases each year are driven by rising production costs and parts obsolescence. The requested funding for FY2026 will support the ongoing modernization and readiness
 of our airdrop capabilities. Upgrading to Block 4.1 JPADS systems (ACUs and UHFs) is necessary to ensure our aircraft can continue to perform these vital missions in compliance with Military Standard (MIL-
 STD)-810H and MIL-STD-704F requirements, and Operational Safety, Suitability, and Effectiveness (OSS&E) requirements in Air Force Materiel Command Instruction (AFMCI) 63-1201.

