Justification:
PE 0201122F US Central Command (USCENTCOM) Communications

In FY 2026, USCENTCOM will continue transitioning all networking, computer-based operations, and secure information to a hybrid multi-cloud architecture. This transition supports USCENTCOM's two
headquarters, a Pentagon liaison office, Security Cooperation Organizations (SCO) sites, and a data backup/disaster recovery (DR) location (SITE X). This hybrid multi-cloud infrastructure ensures real-time data
access and enables efficient Command and Control (C2) capabilities across all locations.

Currently, the headquarters for USCENTCOM staff supports 18 networks encompassing a minimum of 10,250 user accounts, computers, and peripherals. These networks include SIPRNet, NIPRNet, and
multiple bilateral and multinational coalition networks. FY 2026 funding will also further the development of the USCENTCOM Collaborative Partner Environment (CPE) network, consolidating numerous coalition/
partner networks to create a more responsive and flexible mission command capability with a focus on zero-trust and data centricity

The FY 2026 request for USCENTCOM Comm includes $2000 thousand of discretionary funding.

PE 0201131F Service Support to USCENTCOM Communication

FY 2026 procurement funds for Service Support to USCENTCOM focused on modernizing key infrastructure and capabilities across the Area of Responsibility (AOR). First, base Command, Control,
Communications, Computers, and Intelligence (C4I) infrastructure will be modernized at multiple locations to support the USCENTCOM Theater Posture Plan (TPP) and align with the Joint Information
Environment mandate. This includes funding new air domain awareness technologies and replacing aging Air Traffic Control and Landing Systems. The datalink communications network, crucial for maintaining
air domain awareness across the AOR, will also receive upgrades to comply with mandates from the National Security Agency, National Telecommunications and Information Agency, and the Federal Aviation
Agency for Crypto Modernization and Frequency Remapping capabilities.

To enhance Intelligence, Surveillance, and Reconnaissance (ISR) capabilities, funding will support acquiring a portable family of radars for rapid and precise detection and tracking of airborne targets, including
general aviation aircraft and other potential threats. These radars provide active detection, accurate target position information, and in-flight tracking. Finally, to strengthen Communications Protective Measures,
funding will prioritize installing Explosive Detection Technology (EDT) at main Air Expeditionary Wings (AEWs) to prevent vehicle-borne improvised explosive threats, supporting Air Force Operational Order and
Air Force Instruction security mandates (OPORD 05-04 and DAFI31-101). These investments enhance security, information sharing, and provide a decisive advantage in a complex and dynamic AOR.




