 Justification:
 PE 0708015F: FY 2026 funding procures Rapid Sustainment Modernization equipment including Advanced Manufacturing 3-D printers and coldspray machines, Rapid Sustainment Technologies including
 Automation and Robotics to include but not limited to Robotic Radome Scaling, LADS III System, Robotic Sheet Forming Machine, Rapidly Deployable Hangars, E-drill Systems, Match drill systems, Robotic
 Taping System, F-16 Underbelly Paint System, Thermal Spray multipurpose booth, Teremetrix System Install, LCR Laser Upgrade and CBM+ SBA Boxes. Approved RSIP projects included in the PB.

 3D Printing and Coldspray Equipment - FY2026 increases due to expansion of procurement of various 3D printing technologies for field-units and cold spray depot implementation.

 Automation and Robotics - FY2026 decreases due to FY24PB planned Group 1 funding of Rapid Sustainment Innovation Program (RSIP) for BlackGold, eDrill, and Intermittent Fault Detection ends FY2025.
 Additional projects anticipated in the FY2026 Program Decision Memorandum for Group 3.
 Condition-Based Maintenance+ (CBM+) - FY2026 decreases due to recoding of to O&M due to eaches cost falling under the 350K threshold.

 PE 0207142F: FY 2026 funding procures F-35 Base Procured Equipment to include, a Lightning Modular Extendable Rigid Wall Shelter (LMERWS) which is a secure mobile facility for worldwide deployment
 that fulfills unique requirements for Autonomic Logistics Information System (ALIS)/Operational Data Integrated Network (ODIN), peripherals, F-35 intelligence operations, mission planning, Government Systems
 Security Officer (GSSO), Information Systems Security Officer (ISSO), and allows for pre/post-flight briefings. The F-35 is non-employable without LMERWS to perform mission planning, maintenance, and sortie
 generation. Aircraft Sunshades that provide the F-35 with lightning protection and enable all weather maintenance operations by protecting personnel from inclement and extreme weather conditions. Temporary
 Shelters are required in accordance with F-35 base Interim Operating Plans (IOP). Temporary Shelters allow for the timely delivery of the F-35 and for unit Initial Operating Capability independent of MILCON
 and FSRM project progress. Intrusion Detection Systems (IDS) for F-35 facilities in compliance with AFI 31-101 and ICD 705 requirements. Facilities without IDS cannot have PL resources stored, staged, or
 hangered without being continuously monitored by the owner/user of the facility. Secure spaces that do not meet ICD 705 requirements cannot be accredited and cannot be used to process classified information.
 IDS allows for the full operation and utilization of facilities required for F-35 mission success.

 PE 0804701F: FY 2026 funding procures Advanced Pilot Training System Equipment. After long delays, the first T-7 aircraft will arrive at pilot training bases across the Air Force beginning in FY26. Procurement
 of Sunshades are behind schedule for this arrival. Without Smart Sunshades technology vital training of new AF pilots will be lost with loss of ability to collect aircraft data for mission rehearsal and outbrief. The
 sunshades provide the cover for adverse weather and will aid in keeping the temperature of the electronics inside the aircraft to allow maintenance and pre-flight to occur. Without the sunshades, there could be
 loss of training due to the overheating of the aircraft electronics, and subjecting aircrews and pilots from environmental impacts. Sunshades are critical in the beginning of training all future Air Force Pilots.

 PE 0804731F: FY 2026 funding procures a live fire burn-space trainer required to fulfill evolutions for structural fire, coordinated attack, and hose and sprinkler operations training objectives as required by DoDM
 6055.6, the National Fire Protection Association (NFPA) Standard 1072 and 1000 series, the International Fire Services Accreditation Congress, and ProBoard for 1,300 DoD and International Fire Protection
 Students annually. Trainers provide ability to award 3 of the 6 required national certifications; Firefighter I, Firefighter II, and Airport Rescue Firefighter. The existing burn trainer was built in 1994 and is scheduled
 for demolition in FY25. In 2018, a NFPA 1403 (NFPA live-fire training structure evaluation) was conducted on the trainer and determined to be in extremely poor condition with a recommended to replace
 the trainer as soon as possible. Special Warfare investment equipment supporting the Pararescue/Combat Rescue Officer, Combat Controller/Special Tactics Officer, Tactical Air C2/Air Liaison, and Special
 Operations Weather career fields.



